<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
MALE: Body length 
<quantity box="[448,538,151,176]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" unit="mm" value="7.0" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="6.0">6–8mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis box="[551,621,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Head:</emphasis>
Second segment of labial palpus about 
<number box="[1092,1126,151,176]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="1.5">1.5</number>
x as long as first segment. Antenna not modified, segments 
<number box="[521,577,188,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="8.0" valueMax="13.0" valueMin="3.0">3–13</number>
longer than broad (
<figureCitation box="[797,866,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1880,1902]" captionTargetBox="[187,1411,337,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[187,1411,337,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1: Hoplitis haplophylli, clypeus of female. 2: Hoplitis haplophylli, sterna 3 – 6 of male. 3: Hoplitis haplophylli, terga 4 – 7 of male. 4: Hoplitis haplophylli, antenna of male. 5: Hoplitis taenioceras, antenna of male. 6: Hoplitis heinrichi: tarsus of middle leg. 7: Hoplitis heinrichi: last antennal segment of male. 8: Hoplitis illustris: last antennal segment of male. 9: Hoplitis heinrichi: brood cell in preexisting insect burrow in the ground, which is entirely constructed from chewed leaves; below the cell, a partition of chewed leaves has been built, separating the cell from the lower part of the burrow." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230854/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
Fig. 
<number box="[849,866,188,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
). Antennal segments (
<number box="[1115,1128,188,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="3.0">3</number>
) 
<number box="[1137,1195,188,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="7.5" valueMax="11.0" valueMin="4.0">4–11</number>
(
<number box="[1203,1232,188,212]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="12.0">12</number>
) orange. Distance between lateral ocellus and preoccipital ridge 
<number box="[692,776,224,248]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="2.55" valueMax="2.7" valueMin="2.4">2.4–2.7</number>
x as long as ocellar diameter. 
<taxonomicName authority="Scutum" authorityName="Scutum" box="[1133,1359,224,248]" class="Crustacea" family="Crustacea" genus="Mesosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Crustacea" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1133,1262,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Mesosoma:</emphasis>
Scutum
</taxonomicName>
rather densely punctured with interspaces varying in size between the diameter of less than half a puncture and the diameter of one and a half, rarely two punctures. Scutellum densely punctured with interspaces rarely exceeding the diameter of half a puncture. Basal zone of propodeum shagreened in its upper third and polished in its lower two thirds. Tegula yellowish translucent and indistinctly punctured in its anterior third. 
<collectingCountry box="[1165,1221,367,392]" name="India" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Hind</collectingCountry>
coxa with distinct longitudinal keel. Tarsal segments of middle leg of normal shape, lateroapically without spine-like processes. 
<emphasis box="[151,277,441,464]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Metasoma:</emphasis>
Discs of terga 
<number box="[452,493,439,464]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="3.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="1.0">1–5</number>
densely punctured with interspaces reaching the diameter of one to one and a half punctures; disc of tergum 
<number box="[449,463,476,501]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="6.0">6</number>
less densely punctured with interspaces reaching the diameter of up to three or more punctures. Marginal zones of terga 
<number box="[553,595,511,536]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="3.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="1.0">1–5</number>
yellowish-white to yellowish-brown, very densely punctured with minute punctures except for the apicalmost zone, which is unpunctured. Terga 
<number box="[943,985,548,573]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="3.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="1.0">1–5</number>
with dense apical white hair bands (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1880,1902]" captionTargetBox="[187,1411,337,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[187,1411,337,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1: Hoplitis haplophylli, clypeus of female. 2: Hoplitis haplophylli, sterna 3 – 6 of male. 3: Hoplitis haplophylli, terga 4 – 7 of male. 4: Hoplitis haplophylli, antenna of male. 5: Hoplitis taenioceras, antenna of male. 6: Hoplitis heinrichi: tarsus of middle leg. 7: Hoplitis heinrichi: last antennal segment of male. 8: Hoplitis illustris: last antennal segment of male. 9: Hoplitis heinrichi: brood cell in preexisting insect burrow in the ground, which is entirely constructed from chewed leaves; below the cell, a partition of chewed leaves has been built, separating the cell from the lower part of the burrow." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230854/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,166,584,608]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
), which may be interrupted on terga 
<quantity box="[595,668,583,608]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.81" metricValueMax="5.08" metricValueMin="2.54" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" unit="in" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2 in</quantity>
older specimens. Tergum 
<number box="[972,986,583,608]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="6.0">6</number>
laterally with distinct yellowish-brown tooth separated by a deep roundish incision from the yellowish-brown apical tergal margin, which is slightly protruding medially (
<figureCitation box="[398,471,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1880,1902]" captionTargetBox="[187,1411,337,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[187,1411,337,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1: Hoplitis haplophylli, clypeus of female. 2: Hoplitis haplophylli, sterna 3 – 6 of male. 3: Hoplitis haplophylli, terga 4 – 7 of male. 4: Hoplitis haplophylli, antenna of male. 5: Hoplitis taenioceras, antenna of male. 6: Hoplitis heinrichi: tarsus of middle leg. 7: Hoplitis heinrichi: last antennal segment of male. 8: Hoplitis illustris: last antennal segment of male. 9: Hoplitis heinrichi: brood cell in preexisting insect burrow in the ground, which is entirely constructed from chewed leaves; below the cell, a partition of chewed leaves has been built, separating the cell from the lower part of the burrow." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230854/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
Fig. 
<number box="[455,471,656,680]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Tergum 
<number box="[595,609,656,679]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="7.0">7</number>
quadrate, its yellowish-brown apical margin subtruncate with rounded edges (
<figureCitation box="[232,302,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1880,1902]" captionTargetBox="[187,1411,337,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[187,1411,337,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1: Hoplitis haplophylli, clypeus of female. 2: Hoplitis haplophylli, sterna 3 – 6 of male. 3: Hoplitis haplophylli, terga 4 – 7 of male. 4: Hoplitis haplophylli, antenna of male. 5: Hoplitis taenioceras, antenna of male. 6: Hoplitis heinrichi: tarsus of middle leg. 7: Hoplitis heinrichi: last antennal segment of male. 8: Hoplitis illustris: last antennal segment of male. 9: Hoplitis heinrichi: brood cell in preexisting insect burrow in the ground, which is entirely constructed from chewed leaves; below the cell, a partition of chewed leaves has been built, separating the cell from the lower part of the burrow." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230854/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
Fig. 
<number box="[287,302,692,716]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
). Apical margin of sternum 
<number box="[631,645,692,716]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="1.0">1</number>
sharply edged and slightly protruding medially, of sternum 
<number box="[1338,1352,692,716]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="2.0">2</number>
evenly rounded to medially truncated, of sterna 
<number box="[626,640,728,752]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="3.0">3</number>
and 
<number box="[701,715,727,752]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="5.0">5</number>
slightly emarginated and of sternum 
<number box="[1152,1166,728,752]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="4.0">4</number>
distinctly emarginated. Marginal zones of sterna 
<number box="[465,506,764,789]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="3.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="1.0">1–5</number>
with whitish hair bands, which are longest on sterna 
<number box="[1178,1223,764,788]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4</number>
. Sternum 
<number box="[1350,1364,764,789]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="5.0">5</number>
lacks longitudinal keel or protuberance. Sternum 
<number box="[656,670,799,824]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="6.0">6</number>
medioapically prolonged into long process of narrowly triangular shape (
<figureCitation box="[230,299,836,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1880,1902]" captionTargetBox="[187,1411,337,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[187,1411,337,1859]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1 – 9. 1: Hoplitis haplophylli, clypeus of female. 2: Hoplitis haplophylli, sterna 3 – 6 of male. 3: Hoplitis haplophylli, terga 4 – 7 of male. 4: Hoplitis haplophylli, antenna of male. 5: Hoplitis taenioceras, antenna of male. 6: Hoplitis heinrichi: tarsus of middle leg. 7: Hoplitis heinrichi: last antennal segment of male. 8: Hoplitis illustris: last antennal segment of male. 9: Hoplitis heinrichi: brood cell in preexisting insect burrow in the ground, which is entirely constructed from chewed leaves; below the cell, a partition of chewed leaves has been built, separating the cell from the lower part of the burrow." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/230854/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
Fig. 
<number box="[282,299,836,860]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="165" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,871,896]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Distribution.</emphasis>
Southeastern Central Asia (
<collectingCountry box="[727,862,871,896]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[888,1001,871,896]" name="Tajikistan" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Tajikistan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1028,1159,871,896]" name="Uzbekistan" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Uzbekistan</collectingCountry>
); westernmost record: Samarkand (
<collectingCountry box="[292,425,908,933]" name="Uzbekistan" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Uzbekistan</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,348,943,968]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Pollen hosts.</emphasis>
Probably oligolectic on 
<taxonomicName box="[622,782,943,968]" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Haplophyllum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Julida" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[622,782,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Haplophyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[797,907,944,968]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rutaceae</taxonomicName>
): all 
<number box="[959,987,943,968]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="16.0">16</number>
pollen loads (
<number box="[1148,1160,944,968]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" value="1.0">1</number>
locality) analyzed so far exclusively consisted of 
<taxonomicName box="[427,587,980,1005]" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Haplophyllum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Julida" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[427,587,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Haplophyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
pollen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1112]" box="[199,514,1015,1040]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,389,1015,1040]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Nesting biology.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="165" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[151,1437,151,1112]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1052,1077]" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Etymology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[344,504,1052,1077]" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Haplophyllum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Julida" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[344,504,1052,1077]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">Haplophyllum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
= genus of the 
<taxonomicName box="[699,805,1053,1076]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rutaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rutaceae</taxonomicName>
, referring to the probably exclusive pollen host of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="165">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Hoplitis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="165" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haplophylli">H. haplophylli</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
